reviews.text: I love great Italian food and I especially love great pasta. Living in the West Village of Manhattan affords the opportunity to have some of the best pasta in the country - I Sodi, Via Carota, L’Artusi, Barbuto … - the bar is very high. I ventured a little outside the neighborhood to try A Pasta Bar this evening and wow, I was not disappointed. The meal was outstanding. I was by myself, so I kept it simple - Panne Della Casa to start. Loved it - particularly the ricotta and olive oil dip. The focaccia was super fresh, salty, and flavorful. The pasta - the pasta was incredible. 10/10. I absolutely loved this dish. The Maltagliati with sausage and pumpkin. I love a great bolognese, which is on the menu, and this was similar but unique. The pasta was super fresh and the sauce was rich, meaty and flavorful   I finished with a hazelnut gelato and walked home with a spring in my step. Highly recommend.

reviews.text:
Bar Pitti is a very charming Italian restaurant, really well located and with a lively atmosphere that makes it a great spot to enjoy a meal. The ambience is warm and welcoming, and you’re attended by Italian servers, which adds an authentic touch to the experience.

We started with bruschettas topped with prosciutto, which were excellent—simple yet full of flavor. They also brought fresh bread with olive oil to the table, a nice classic touch. For the main dishes, we tried a few different pastas. The truffle fettuccini was good, but honestly, the truffle flavor wasn’t as strong or rich as we had hoped. The carbonara, on the other hand, was excellent—creamy, flavorful, and definitely the highlight of the meal. The tagliatelle with marinara sauce was fine, though nothing particularly special.

One thing to note is that the restaurant does not accept credit cards, which is quite unusual and a bit inconvenient. On top of that, an automatic 18% gratuity is added to the bill, which I personally did not like, as I prefer to decide the tip myself based on the service.

Overall, Bar Pitti has great vibes, attentive service, and some solid dishes—especially the carbonara. But the payment policy and the mandatory gratuity are definitely something to keep in mind before going.

places.address: 181 Thompson St, New York, NY 10012, USA

reviews.text:
We dined at Carbone many years ago, before all the hype, and at the time thought it was a solid experience with generous portions. This visit, however, I completely understand the buzz.

Despite being 20 minutes late to our reservation, we were graciously seated on a packed Saturday night — a great first impression. The Caesar salad was phenomenal, with bold flavors and an unforgettable sauce. The beef tartare and spicy vodka rigatoni were definite standouts.

The ribeye was good but felt a bit heavy with the sauce. Dessert more than made up for it — the carrot cake with ginger ice cream was excellent.

What truly sets Carbone apart is the ambiance. Cozy, intimate, and beautifully styled with real candles and timeless music, it feels like stepping into a glamorous 1960s supper club. Elegant, lively, and full of character — a memorable dining experience from start to finish.
reviews.author: Yuliya Lubin

reviews.text:
Carbone exceeded every expectation while we celebrated my husband’s birthday here! From the moment we arrived, the service was impeccable from all the staffs: warm, welcoming.

This restaurant is incredibly hard to get into, and it absolutely lives up to the hype. The energy is electric, the room is buzzing, and the hospitality feels elevated and personal. Eddie was our main guy and was phenomenal! He so attentive and thoughtful. Michuel was also wonderful, making sure everything flowed seamlessly.

The food was delicious, rich, and comforting. The experience as a whole felt special from start to finish.

If you’re celebrating something meaningful or just want to experience one of NYC’s most iconic restaurants, Carbone is worth every bit of the hype.

reviews.text:
This reviews about sustainability only! 🙂

By 2050, there will be more plastic in the ocean than fish—and over 95% of plastic does not actually get recycled.

I was pretty shocked to see that every single person enjoying their coffee at your lovely café, to stay, was drinking out of a single use plastic cup. One that will get used for 30 to 60 minutes, and then get discarded to a landfill or end up eventually in our oceans where it’ll stay for the next 400 years.

I see that you do have plates available, and seemingly real mugs too. I wonder then if there is a disconnect between your customers and the availability of more sustainable options.

Are there ways that you can ask people if they are enjoying their drink to stay? And if so, would you be able to give them a real mug or glass? Or, could you use your social media to help raise awareness about bringing your own reusable cup?

Of course, this problem is as much on the consumer as the business. So I hope any customers or potential reading this know that they can and should bring their own cup, to prevent more plastic pollution.

Thank you for hearing my concerns, I would be happy to help think through easy options that would help you all mitigate contribution to our global pollution crisis. In a waterfront neighborhood in a water-locked borough, it just makes sense to think beyond so much plastic.

And of course, if you do not actually have dish dishwashing infrastructure, I can understand your challenge. But if so, surely there’s a way you can at least be incentivizing people bringing their own cups.

Thank you again for your consideration. And for the delicious coffee.

reviews.text:
Variety Coffee on Graham Ave is hands-down my favorite spot in Williamsburg. The baristas are genuinely some of the kindest, most welcoming people—you walk in and they remember your usual, always with a smile and zero attitude. The coffee is consistently outstanding: their Lucky Shot espresso pulls are rich and fruity, the iced oat milk lattes are creamy perfection, and the seasonal pour-overs never miss.
Love that it feels like a real neighborhood cafe—great playlist, plenty of seats, natural light, and that classic Brooklyn vibe without trying too hard. Pastries (especially the vegan blueberry muffin) are always fresh, and the prices are totally fair for the quality.
Whether I’m grabbing a quick cold brew on my way to the L train or camping out with my laptop for a couple hours, it’s always a good experience. Huge thanks to the whole crew for making mornings better. Williamsburg is lucky to have you! ☕❤️

personalization.forUser: If Hungry Ghost Coffee has a calm and focused environment, it would be suitable for Alex's work, regardless of specific cuisine or genre preferences.

places.address: 337 5th Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11215, USA

reviews.text: I ordered a matcha latte iced and a blueberry muffin and they both tasted nice! Great for studying and working cozy, calm and amazing style of music! Love this place I recommend. ☕️
reviews.author: lia

reviews.text: Nice coffee spot. Good location, coffee and service. Clean and calm place to enjoy your cup of coffee and look outside through the windows.
reviews.author: Fred D.

reviews.text: Delicious coffee, good sweet and savory offerings (just a bit pricey). The staff is attentive and extremely efficient. It’s not always easy to find a table, but it’s a perfect spot for coffee on the go.
reviews.author: Virginia Podesta

query: romantic dinner spots in the West Village

personalization.forUser: Given Alex's preference for Italian cuisine, The Eighty Six offers a cozy and potentially romantic setting for a dinner date.

places.address: 86 Bedford St, New York, NY 10014, USA

reviews.text: Everything about this is NYC. No sign on the door and it looks a like an if you know you know kinda place from the outside. Stepping inside is old school vibes with art deco. A real fireplace really set the ambiance. To go with the cool vibes is some great food. Everything we had was fantastic. Some really unique items on the menu that are executed flawlessly like the French onion croquettes, cheesesteak and all the desserts. Would definitely recommend.
reviews.author: KC

reviews.text: Nothing about this restaurant was anything short of 5 stars. We sat at the bar and Shawn the bartender was attentive and knowledgeable. The oysters were fresh with a delicious mignonette. The Delmonico steak had a perfect char. The Caesar salad croutons were warm and crisp with a soft inside. Unlike any Caesar I’ve ever had. The drinks were curated to our taste and adapted beautifully. History and ambiance are unmatched. All the staff were warm and professional. We took a risk as walk ins without a reservation and it paid off.
reviews.author: Peter Gibbons

reviews.text: One of the best dinners we have had in a long time. Don greeted us at the door and Francesco took good care of us at the bar. The pasta dish was a standout that I’m happy we ordered. But you have to come for the cheese steak and the strip. 10/10 meal and really nice ambiance inside. Amazing addition from the Catch team.
reviews.author: Tyler Heffernan

personalization.forUser: With Alex's love for Italian food, Palma's charming atmosphere and focus on Italian cuisine make it a potentially appealing choice.

places.address: 28 Cornelia St, New York, NY 10014, USA

reviews.text: This was undoubtedly one of the best Italian meals I’ve had since living in NYC! Highly recommend the carciofi fritti (fried calamari), arancini (risotto balls), ravioli Cacio e Pepe (very rich) and Candele Spezzate alla Genovese with GF pene (INCREDIBLE)!!! The La Vie en Rose cocktail was refreshing and the Brunello was delicious. The atmosphere at lunchtime was lovely and the staff were are super friendly. I cannot wait to come back to this restaurant and try everything! The menu was clearly labeled for gluten free, vegetarian and vegan options. Staff was able to easily accommodate allergies to gluten, nuts, coconut and sesame.
reviews.author: Elizabeth Sara Ross

reviews.text: Such a beautifully decorated and charming restaurant serving some of the best Italian cuisine I have ever had! Their homemade pastas were incredibly executed, and the flavors were out of this world. The Focaccia and olive oil came out warm and perfectly toasted. The risotto was truly life changing and an absolute must try. Highly recommend dining in the covered outdoor patio as the atmosphere was wonderful. Palma has easily become one of my favorites of all time! Would come back again and again as this place is a destination in itself.
reviews.author: Mel D

reviews.text:
We finally made it to Palma and everything was fantastic. It was the day after Christmas and it was snowing so it was quieter than usual according to the bartender, Kacey. She was fantastic and made perfect recommendations.

We had the focaccia, Tuna Tartare, octopus, meatballs, and Candele Spezzate alla Genovese. Everything was delicious, perfectly balanced and seasoned especially the Candele which we were told is seasonal so it will be off the menu by spring. Go get it!!

We finished with one the best tiramisus we’ve ever had.
reviews.author: Justin Cohen

personalization.forUser: While not specifically aligning with Alex's cuisine preferences, Café Cluny's reputation for a romantic ambiance might still make it a good option.

places.address: 284 W 12th St, New York, NY 10014, USA

reviews.text:
We were here for dinner. The pan-seared salmon was perfectly cooked, the shallots and puree was Chef’s kiss although i found the salad to be very acidic than usual. The linguine was buttery and delicious.
For desserts I wish the sticky toffee pudding was less sweet but it was moist and well made. I was not a fan of profiteroles filled with ice cream as it made it so heavy. I usually like it with pastry cream. Choux pastry was not crispy, not the best. Hot chocolate had a slight malted flavor which was pleasant- right amount of chocolate and sweetness.

Service and ambience were excellent.
reviews.author: Aafrin Fathima

reviews.text: Cute cozy bistro with great vibe and tasty food. Highly recommend if you are looking for a nice spot in West village. The menus covers good numbers of classic dishes and vegetarian options are available and great coffee.
reviews.author: Azadeh Nematzadeh

reviews.text:
It was one of the best restaurant experiences ever in NYC! Absolutely charming atmosphere and delicious food! Our server took care of us and recommended professionally cocktails pairing what made our dinner more memorable!
Will be back to try the brunch menu!
reviews.author: Vyacheslav “Slava” D.

personalization.forUser: Although it doesn't directly match Alex's cuisine preferences, Hudson Clearwater's focus on fresh, seasonal ingredients may appeal to a sophisticated palate.

places.address: 447 Hudson St, New York, NY 10014, USA

reviews.text: Brunch or dinner is always incredible!! The chefs seasonal menu’s are first class. Beautiful patio seating outside, or the chef counter inside to watch the magic happen. Classy interior is comfortable any time year and the marble bar is well stocked and first come first serve! There’s also a private wine cellar for larger groups!
reviews.author: Boz Kramer

reviews.text: A quintessential brunch spot with good food and lovely atmosphere. Delicious arugula salad, phenomenal duck hash, and a dark chocolate bread pudding that smoulders in its tastiness. You definitely should visit.
reviews.author: Farid Hamka

reviews.text:
Overpriced inconsistent food with a few standout dishes, good service, unbearably loud indoor space with terrible acoustics.

I came here with a few friends and we ordered a variety of apps and sides to share, multiple rounds of drinks, and entrees. Of the food, the sweet potatoes, fried artichokes, and burrata were exceptional. Everything else was pretty bad. My steak, which I ordered rare, was tough and cooked medium well so it was barely edible. My pot of chocolate was very gritty.

My friends enjoyed the scallops and gnocchi but I didn't enjoy my entree or dessert at all.

Great attentive service.

The worst part was how insanely loud the place is with no dampening so it was like being in a noise conversation tunnel all night. Probably the outside seating is better.

Overall, the food and drinks are a bit overpriced for the iffy quality. We spent over $500 for 4 people.
reviews.author: Yiyi Zhang

personalization.forUser: While not strictly Italian, Japanese, or Mexican, Tartine's reputation for quality and atmosphere could still make it suitable for a romantic dinner.

places.address: 253 W 11th St, New York, NY 10014, USA

reviews.text: Tartine benefits from being in a prime spot within NYC and I think the prices reflect the same. The space is tiny but really well done. Food was good but had limited vegetarian options and they don’t offer substitutions. I should also note that I was here for brunch with friends and a couple of us don’t consume eggs which made it harder.
reviews.author: Kartik Bharadwaj

reviews.text: The food was good. The place is small which is great. However if you have back problems please note the seats on the edge  of restaurant have the window as the back. If you have back issues you’ll want to sit in the middle for support. They French onion soup is a+. The burger is fine. It’s a bit over flavored with to many flavors at once but in all it was nice. No ketchup or other dipping sauces which is fine, but the burger was a bit dry to have nothing to dip in
reviews.author: Zachary Farley

reviews.text:
Tartine – Our Forever Favorite in the West Village

Some places feed you more than food—and Tartine is one of those rare, irreplaceable spots.

Tucked into the dreamiest little corner of the West Village, Tartine is where my husband and I had our very first date night. It’s where he took me for my first birthday after we met. And later, it’s where we shot part of our wedding photos. Even my husband’s colleagues gifted us wedding anniversary gift card from Tartine ! That’s how personal this place is to us.

We’ve been back more times than I can count, and it’s never just about the food (though the food is always good). It’s about the energy, the people, the warmth. The staff are some of the kindest you’ll meet in New York—no pretense, just genuine hospitality. Even though they don’t take reservations, you never feel rushed or forgotten. People wait patiently, because everyone seems to know: it’s worth it.

The food? Honest. Generous. Comforting. There’s nothing overly fussy—just really well-made dishes that feel like home. My go-to is the crab cake when it’s available (an underrated gem), and if you’re lucky, the white frosted cheesecake will be on the menu—soft, light, and absolutely dreamy. My husband swears by the burger. The menu changes often enough to keep things exciting, but the soul of it stays the same.

In summer, Tartine is extra magical. The leafy West Village corner, the big windows, the sunlight filtering in—it’s the kind of spot you want to sit at for hours with someone you love. But even on a rainy or gloomy day, something about it lifts your mood. It just feels good to be there.

Tartine may not be flashy or trendy, but that’s exactly why we love it. It’s one of those truly underrated places that deserves to be cherished—and we’ll keep coming back, again and again💗💗💗
reviews.author: Zoe

personalization.forUser: Although it doesn't clearly align with Alex's favorite cuisines, The Little Owl's cozy and intimate setting might be a good fit for a romantic dinner.

places.address: 90 Bedford St, New York, NY 10014, USA

reviews.text: Little Owl was established in 2006. I have had this restaurant in my radar for many years but it took me 19 years to finally dine here. I wish I discovered this gem of a restaurant sooner. The vibe is of a comfy cozy neighborhood restaurant. We enjoyed the French onion soup, meatball sliders and the Bibb and Beets salad. The salad was absolutely delicious and worth coming back for that dish alone. I enjoyed my non-alcoholic drink but found the desserts a tad too sweet for my taste. The service was excellent. Jorge was especially hospitable and made us feel welcomed. I will be back soon.
reviews.author: Susan Seto

reviews.text: I had an incredible experience at Little Owl. Suggested to me by a friend‘s mother. It did not disappoint. If you’re going, definitely get the halibut. A very unique yet simple way of cooking the fish. The story goes that it used to be grilled until the grill went out in the first week and they’ve decided to broil ever since. They really go over and above to make sure you’re comfortable as well. It was very nice to feel well taken care of.
reviews.author: Hannah Clark

reviews.text: Little Owl — tucked right under the iconic "Friends" apartment building — is a must-stop in the West Village. Cozy, welcoming, and absolutely delicious. The meatball is non-negotiable: tender, perfectly seasoned, and sauced just right. Service is friendly, the vibe is intimate, and every plate feels thoughtfully made. Come hungry, order the meatball first, and grab a quick photo outside afterward. Perfect NYC spot!
reviews.author: M M

personalization.forUser: While primarily a bar, Dante NYC's Italian influence and stylish ambiance could be appealing given Alex's preference for Italian cuisine.

places.address: 551 Hudson St, New York, NY 10014, USA

reviews.text:
Wonderful, attentive service and top-quality food across the board.
Oysters first — magnificent. The fish was excellent, the steak outstanding, the soup delightful, and the mushroom risotto cooked to perfection.

We dined as a family of four, with our two daughters. The quality and balance of the dishes stood out — superb produce, very much in the vein of European ingredients and cooking.

The interior is equally lovely. Booking can be a challenge — we were fortunate walk-ins. Thank you for keeping a table for the unplanned; it was much appreciated.
reviews.author: Jan Rockstroh

reviews.text:
I love this place! The cocktail menu is fabulous. I got a Negroni Bianco. So good. My group was eating at 10:30 PM so ate light and were impressed by the numerous options that wouldn’t weigh you down before bedtime. I had a delicious salad with arugula and smoked trout. My vegetarian daughter had a cauliflower dish along with some grilled pumpkin. Another had a burrata appetizer and one ordered the cheeseburger. That cheeseburger was more than she could consume.
All of the cocktails were well balanced. One was enough. I’ll be back. Great vibe! Ram, our waiter, was terrific and the staff worked well as a team.
reviews.author: Pamela A

reviews.text:
Storied little pub in the West Village.
Wonderfully designed interior. Rustic, inviting, and welcoming.
Went by myself to try a martini during their martini hour.
Alive enough to have fun but quiet enough to have a conversation with friends. I would have loved to have come by with friends!
reviews.author: Joon Lim

personalization.forUser: Although it specializes in French cuisine, Boucherie West Village offers a sophisticated and romantic atmosphere that might be appealing.

places.address: 99 7th Ave S, New York, NY 10014, USA

reviews.text:
We enjoyed a rather luxurious meal at Boucherie; the service was quick and friendly and the quality of food was great. We visited this restaurant for our first night in NYC as I heard they went all out with Christmas decorations and that the atmosphere would be unmatched. Upon entering the restaurant, we were met with an incredibly bustling environment with not a single empty seat. The Christmas decorations were lovely and the space was packed with holiday spirit. I feel like the tables could not have been more close together; they were really making use of all of the available floor space they had.

We were seated at a nice table on the second floor, which was not the most spacious, however still nice. Some of the seats at the 4-person table overlooked the ground floor and provided such a beautiful view. Onto the food, our waitress was very helpful and assured me that they could get me something different if I didn't like what I was served. I ordered the confit de canard and my two friends ordered the steak frites. Although pricey for sure, the steak frites lived up to our expectations, as it was delicious and cooked to our liking. The duck leg, however, was a little disappointing as a lot of the meat was dry, as if it was left in the oven for too long. Consequently, it was hard to bite and felt dry. I don't think it was worth the $44USD. Finally, we were quite appalled by the price of one glass of coke --- my friend ordered a glass and got a refill because the glass was mostly filled with ice, and it ultimately ran us up $18!!!! That was pretty insane but I guess it's a fancier restaurant, so we should be more cautious next time.

All in all, we had an enjoyable experience dining at Boucherie and it lived up to our expectations. If you're willing to spend a pretty penny for decent food and a wonderful atmosphere, definitely check it out!
reviews.author: Karen Liu

reviews.text:
We had a great dinner at Boucherie and really enjoyed the experience. The atmosphere is beautiful and cozy, perfect for a nice evening in New York. Our server, Ash, took great care of us the whole time, super kind, helpful, and very professional.

The food was amazing from start to finish. We ordered the steak with fries, the steak tartare, and some desserts, and everything was delicious and very well prepared. The crème brûlée and the chocolate dessert were outstanding.

It was a wonderful dinner and we definitely recommend Boucherie to anyone visiting NYC or looking for a great French restaurant. We’d be happy to come back next time we’re in the city.
reviews.author: leandro lima

reviews.text:
We have been trying to get in so we came for brunch.
From the moment we hit the door, service was impeccable. YAMAN was our server and was one of the best we have ever had.
We sat near the beautiful tree.
I ordered the steak frites and a vanilla strawberry croissant,
My wife ordered the eggs Benedict.  We did splits

Steak Frites- good amazingly- so moist and flavorful- came with butter and a pepper brown sauce on the side- so good

Eggs Benedict- just perfect. Nothing else to say

The croissant was stuffed with strawberry marmalade and a vanilla cream on top. This was amazing.

A must visit-  service, food and ambiance are top notch. YAMAN thank you for a great day.
reviews.author: Sean Simmons

personalization.forUser: Since Alex likes Japanese cuisine, Wild Cherry can be a good option to try.

places.address: 38 Commerce St, New York, NY 10014, USA

reviews.text: Wild Cherry brings Old Hollywood elegance to the West Village. The service is impeccable, the cocktails are thoughtfully crafted, and the food is both high quality and delicious. We ordered the oysters, the Frog Legs Kiev, and the steak dinner for two. Every dish was exceptional, with the Frog Legs Kiev being my personal favorite. I would highly recommend Wild Cherry to anyone who appreciates excellent food, a sense of theatre, and a genuinely fun night out.
reviews.author: Evan Martinez

reviews.text:
Diner aesthetic meets French cuisine is an intriguing twist, but not necessarily needed. The ambiance, though charming, felt at times like a Times Square attraction. The curved ceiling and thin walls amplified sound, making it difficult to hear the one you were dining with.

Service was fine, attentive, but not at the level you’d expect from the people behind Frenchette and Le Veau d’or. It was clear it was all hands on deck, but that left the bathroom a mess and missed opportunities for real hospitality.

The food was priced somewhat high for what it was — it lacked the richness French cuisine should have but the menu items did have the nostalgic comfort diner food brings. The Alfredo and rice and beans were charming!

What they did do right was the martini, but you can find many a good martini in Manhattan and with more intimate atmosphere and hospitable service.
reviews.author: Rach

reviews.text:
Took me three weeks to get a reservation and I was really happy with coming here despite inclement weather. Both hostess and the First Gentleman I spoke to Nicolas were very kind and helpful! I had to run in and out because I work but I had the coconut cake! It was delicious! I was at the bar though and I didn’t try the food but if I get another reservation I most definitely will try the menu!

Get loud though but it was party to the side of me liquor glasses all over the table..so there’s that. However, it was a nice little date for me to me and will be back especially for that cake.

Thank you!!

Leandra
reviews.author: Leandra Wilkerson

personalization.forUser: With Alex's love for Italian food, Via Carota's focus on Italian cuisine makes it a potentially appealing choice.

places.address: 51 Grove St, New York, NY 10014, USA

reviews.text:
We had been wanting to go to Via Carota for a long time and could never get a reservation. We decided to put our name down and were given a table in 45 minutes — worth every single minute of the wait.

Absolutely sublime food. You can truly tell how much care goes into everything they do. The fresh egg pastas are outstanding, the salad was spectacular, and the bruschetta with house-made bread was incredible. Everything was flawless.

The space is super cozy and beautiful, and the service was a solid 10/10.

The egg tagliatelle with prosciutto was one of the best pasta dishes I’ve ever had in my life. That butter… simply wow. No words.

10/10 — we will definitely be back. 🍝✨
reviews.author: Lourdes Ruhstaller

reviews.text: We had a very memorable dinner here. The ambience is surprisingly calm and non pretentious. Had to wait for 20 mins on a Thursday night which was fine because there was excellent jazz being played next door at Arthur’s which you could enjoy. Folks in the restaurant were nicest. We ordered the specials pasta and bruschetta. Everything we had was just excellent. One of those places which makes west village special 💝
reviews.author: Rajarshi Das

reviews.text:
Excellent classic Italian.

Heard a lot about Via Carota and Chef Jody Williams, and when it was recognized by North America’s Best 50 last year, I finally decided to give it a try. We came for a weekday lunch and were seated without a wait at the communal table in the back. Still thoughtfully spaced, with an empty seat between groups.

Given Chef Williams’s background, the menu was a mix of Tuscan and Roman. Territory I’m fairly familiar with coming from Boston. We ordered a few classics like the grilled artichoke, cacio e pepe, and potato ravioli ragu (daily special). Portions were a bit small for the price, but the execution was flawless.

One thing we really loved was their iconic cacio e pepe. Most trattorias I’ve been to rely on dried pasta for a firmer al dente bite, but Chef Williams used fresh pasta across the menu. And it worked beautifully here. Silky and supple, yet still retaining a satisfying snap. More importantly, the sauce had a bold, unapologetic pepperiness that I’ve never felt before from other trattorias in the U.S.

Perhaps Via Carota might not be a place people chase for excitement, but it’s the kind of restaurant I’d regularly visit if it was in my neighborhood. Highly recommend giving them a try for comforting, well-executed Italian classics.
reviews.author: Jea Kim

personalization.forUser: As Alex enjoys Japanese cuisine, Sushi Azabu, known for its high-quality sushi, would be a great fit.

places.address: 428 Greenwich St, New York, NY 10013, USA

reviews.text: Top-notch Japanese quality at a reasonable price. The atmosphere and taste were exceptional, especially the six-piece sushi set, which was outstanding. As a nice touch, Shota and his team served us hot green tea at the end. Highly recommend!
reviews.author: Kohei

reviews.text:
One word to describe this establishment-inconsistent.
I have visited Azabu 4 times and ordered delivery once,which of course would deem my rating as precise as one can get.
It is such a shame, because I sincerely enjoy this restaurant and would even give it a high 4 star on days the Head chef is working. On days he is not available or on vacation it is an absolute disaster service wise and the food is almost a 2 star rating. Everything is Chewy, pale, horribly cut. When he is available everything is pristine. Buttery, fresh, delicious. Take a look at my depressing 150$ delivery order. My Otoro looks like it’s a phantom of yesterday’s Tuna. Better to close your restaurant on days the head chef isn’t available then keep open and lose clients.
reviews.author: Donia Aduna

reviews.text:
Loved it! Multiple Omakase menus to choose from. Intimate wooden interior. Definitely prefer the counter for two diners however a table for three or more is recommended.
Denshin Yuki was chosen for us by the manager and exquisite. Still going strong after so many years. Definitely on the end of the scale but worth it.
reviews.author: Chris M

personalization.forUser: Brushstroke offers a refined Japanese dining experience, aligning with Alex's preference for Japanese cuisine.

places.address: 30 Hudson St, New York, NY 10013, USA

reviews.text: Having eaten many tonkotsu ramens around the city, I was curious about the creativity behind the Bouley team and opted for a different noodle soup. The broth is a thick and creamy concoction of soymilk and white miso that pairs well with the thick udon (thick flat strands like fettucine). The lobster claw is perfectly poached, and the side of nori to garnish adds another layer of umami. The 8-seater around the bar adds to an intimate feel within the beautiful and tranquil setting!
reviews.author: Andy Ng

reviews.text:
Allegedly "underground" and "little-known," this is attached to Brushstroke in the spot that used to be a similarly incredible sushi-bar.

It transformed into an excellent ramen shop, specializing in tonkotsu broth ramen (but others are available).
reviews.author: Jerry Levine

reviews.text:
If you're into bourgeois places, then it's a great start. If not, be open minded and look pass the bourgeoisness. This place is legit. Trust me, I'm Asian. I know my ramen.
For the food, I had the wagyu garlic gyoza and it was fantastic. It taste like a high class burger in a gyoza wrap. Its fantastic. Try it. The sauce was some kind of ponzu sauce. Strong citrus flavor. If you know what calamansi is, that's what will remind you of. Its not overpowering and dip it with th bitterness of the mustard and it's a great compliment to th flavors. Not quite a flavor explosion of grilled wagyu but great none the less.
The tonkotsu ramen is worth going back for. Thick tonkotsu broth, chasu that just falls off, noodles that are firm yet melts slightly in your mouth. A fried chopped garlic and chili sauce are great with it as well but I encourage you to take it in as is and have chili little by little by making a little ramen on your spoon. This place is worth it. Go.
Oishi kata.
reviews.author: Fulbert Cue

personalization.forUser: Tetsu provides a sophisticated sushi experience that caters to Alex's liking for Japanese food.

places.address: 78 Leonard St, New York, NY 10013, USA

reviews.text:
Fantastic experience. It was a journey of unexpected flavors. It’s exceptional to be able to enjoy Masa’s mastery in this outstanding location. There are so many different nooks and crannies in this place. The two Michelin stars are well deserved.

If you go make a point of visiting the downstairs space where you see how the same amount of space is allocated to the guests as to the kitchen.

The chefs were very friendly and took the time to explain and enlighten.
reviews.author: Ziad Iskandar

reviews.text: One of the best burgers in the city, genuinely. The blend of sushi and then burger is a wonderful combination and should be adopted in other places. The bar is a great place to sit because you can watch the food being made. The sushi is amazing of course.
reviews.author: Omar Aly

reviews.text: Beautiful restaurant by chef mass in TriBeCa. Close to the canal st subway stations. They have big windows that open up and there are tables inside next to them - snatch one if you can! (No outdoor seating). Great bar with creative cocktails and nice sake and wine. They have an amazing happy hour menu including $5 fried chicken and $8 sparkling rose. There’s a yuzu cake with yuzu cream and grilled peaches that’s delicious!
reviews.author: W Gmail

personalization.forUser: Shiki Omakase offers a curated sushi experience, perfect for someone like Alex who appreciates Japanese cuisine.

places.address: 71 W Houston St, New York, NY 10012, USA

reviews.text:
Nice little omakase restaurant, very good service. Food was fresh, raw fish was room temperature, all servings made before your eyes. Otoro was the best but their specials like Winter and Summer creations were really good, $18 each.
Had the 17 pieces omakase. Menu was standard and the items were decent. Serving size of the sushi pieces varied from small to regular.
Not much conversation or interaction with the chefs as they were quiet and busy making the foods. I had better omakase experience with chefs.
Decent prices for the amount of food.
reviews.author: Peter Yong (PedroJoven)

reviews.text:
Great quality, flavorful, and very well done omakase at a reasonable price. Had the 17 course menu for $100 at lunch time. They also offer a 12 course menu for $65. Both menus offer a good variety of fish and flavor combinations. The courses are definitely more classic and traditional but well done and tasty.

The interior is small; feels like proper Japan. But it’s a comfortable noise level — some quiet background music, which makes it easy to talk.

The omakase chefs don’t really explain much about the food — they just name the fish and dish when they serve you. You can see how they prepare everything right in front of you. The pace of the courses are good. Nice attention to detail from the chefs: I’ve been here twice and both times when the chef noticed that I was left-handed, they placed the food at the different side of the plate.

Service is attentive and quick.
The second time I was here, we were celebrating my sister’s birthday. At the end, they dimmed the lights, switched from their mellow instrumental  background music to 50 Cents - In Da Club playing on high volume, gave my sister a sparkler, and served her another sushi course with a candle, and the entire team danced to the song for about 30 seconds. Best birthday recognition I’ve ever seen from a restaurant staff.
reviews.author: Jasmin

reviews.text: Was able to snag a resy at this place very last minute (I think day of) for the last 3 seats at the bar at the last serving time they had on a Saturday night. The way this meal changed my entire mood in a short 90 minute seating. This was some of the best omakase I have had in the city and for the best price I've been able to find. The fish was fresher than could be and every single course was delectable and yummy. I left actually feeling pretty full (which can be tough at omakase experiences sometimes) and throughly enjoyed the entire dining experience. Even though we were the last ones at the bar, they never rushed us and made our time together really special. Would love to bring a big group and take over the entire sushi bar, it was that good!!!
reviews.author: Josh Rose

personalization.forUser: Blue Ribbon Sushi is a well-regarded sushi restaurant that matches Alex's interest in Japanese cuisine.

places.address: 119 Sullivan St, New York, NY 10012, USA

reviews.text: Great sushi restaurant. I enjoy the pickled vegetable plate. the eggplant was a delight. the escarole had a lot of depth of flavor. The spinach in sesame was a starter I'd go back for again. It is pricey, however the sushi and sashimi are of great quality and are well crafted. The atmosphere is great. Compact and lively.
reviews.author: carlos borges

reviews.text:
I came to Blue Ribbon Sushi about two years ago and had an amazing experience — a big sushi platter that cost around $200 and felt well worth it. I recently went back for a quick date night, and while the food was still good, the prices have gotten insanely high. I know inflation is real, but this felt pretty extreme.

We ordered the crispy rice with spicy tuna, the Hamachi Serrano, two pieces of otoro sushi, the Unadon, plus one basic bottle of hot sake. The total came out to about $180 including tip, which honestly blew my mind given how little food we actually got.

The otoro sushi especially was disappointing — each piece was around $18, and the slice of fish on top was tiny. It didn’t taste bad, but for that price, I expected something more memorable. Overall, the food was decent but definitely not worth what we paid — and I left still feeling hungry.

On the positive side, the service was excellent. The staff was super attentive and managed to seat us last minute even though the place was fully booked. The restaurant itself is small, cozy, and great for a date night, but I’d just say be prepared to spend a lot more than you’d expect.

In short, the food is fine, the vibe is nice, but the prices are over the top for what you get. I wouldn’t recommend it for a casual dinner unless you’re ready to splurge.
reviews.author: Chloe

reviews.text:
I just left Blue Ribbon Sushi NYC completely disappointed — and still hungry. I paid $57 for food that wasn’t worth half of it. The menu is confusing, with no clear prices, and shrimp tempura wasn’t even listed. When it came, it was just four tiny pieces for $18 — bland, forgettable, and definitely not fresh.

But the worst part was the rude service. I politely asked the waiter if I could charge my phone, and he disappeared. When he finally came back, instead of being helpful, he said, “So, are you ordering more or not?”
That attitude alone ruined the experience. No warmth, no hospitality — just a feeling that I was an inconvenience for not ordering fast enough.

I only went there because Sushi Lin across the street doesn’t have a full kitchen at this location — I really wish they did. I would have had a better meal and much better service.

Overall: Overpriced sushi, unfriendly staff, terrible customer service, and poor value.
If you’re in NYC and want good sushi, skip Blue Ribbon Sushi — there are far better options nearby that actually care about their customers.
reviews.author: Elnaz E

personalization.forUser: Nobu Downtown is a globally recognized Japanese restaurant that would appeal to Alex's preference for Japanese food.

places.address: 195 Broadway, New York, NY 10007, USA

reviews.text:
I rarely write negative reviews, but this experience was a letdown from start to finish. Despite having a reservation, we were forced to wait 20 minutes while the reception staff treated us with arrogance and dismissal.
The dining area is in the basement; it was incredibly loud, stuffy, and poorly ventilated. It felt suffocating rather than high-end.

The Food:
We were a table of four and spent $550, yet left completely unsatisfied. Most hot dishes were oily, heavy on seasoning, or lacked quality.

• Glacier 51 Sea Bass ($56): Supposed to be truffle and miso, but had zero flavor of either.
• A5 Wagyu New Style: A waste of premium meat. It tasted overwhelmingly of generic soy sauce.
• Squid Pasta: Essentially just wok-fried vegetables with squid. I’d expect this at a casual Chinese restaurant, not here.
• Shiitake Salad ($30): Way too oily.
• Miso Soup ($9): Tasted exactly like instant soup.
• Salmon Tartare: Heavily over-seasoned and the portion size was pathetic.
• New Style White Fish: The flavor profile was just weird.
• Grilled Salmon ($40): Oily and unremarkable.
• Sushi: The nigiri ($8/piece) was average at best. The Salmon Tacos were too salty, though the Lobster Tacos were passable.

The Service:
The service was as poor as the food. Haha when I left a standard 15% tip, he sneered at me.

If you are looking for authentic Japanese food or a pleasant environment, go elsewhere. Nobu worldwide seems to be resting on its name rather than quality. Don't go.
reviews.author: Gigi Wu

reviews.text: Over the weekend (Sunday) I was taken here for my birthday. Restaurant wasn't busy, so it was a quiet evening. It was our 1st time. Our server Sigar (apologies if I spelled that wrong) went over the menu with us & helped us choose. Our drinks, the crispy rice, black cod, doughnuts & everything else we ordered was very good. Our waiter was attentive and very nice to us. I plan to go back soon.
reviews.author: L C

reviews.text: My experience at Nobu Downtown was absolutely amazing. The service was impeccable—attentive, professional, and perfectly timed. I tried the tasting menu, and it was truly worth it. Every dish was beautifully presented and bursting with flavor. From start to finish, everything was delicious. Highly recommend for a special night out in New York!
reviews.author: Bruno Rangel

personalization.forUser: Zutto Japanese American Pub offers a casual Japanese dining experience which aligns with Alex's interest in Japanese cuisine.

places.address: 77 Hudson St, New York, NY 10013, USA

reviews.text:
Zutto is the kind of spot you come with friends and end up staying all night. Fun drinks, a beautifully loaded sushi boat made for sharing, and steaming bowls of ramen that bring it all together. Casual, cozy, and full of flavor. The sushi boat is customizable. You can choose any sushi rolls from their large variety of sushi. Definitely worth it!

Follow me @foodie.elite on IG and Tiktok for more!
reviews.author: Foodie Elite

reviews.text: Zutto in Tribeca is one of those laidback chill type Japanese restaurant that offers Japanese street-style food to omakase. Step inside and you will notice the amazing crowd with laughters and excitement in a cozy setting. Not only does Zutto have Japanese sake, whisky, and beer but their handcrafted cocktails is definitely not to be missed. Their sushi boats is a spectacular deal for an entire party or whole entire group! Fill it up with your favorites and it will arrive on a boat that mesmerizes everyone. Each dish and piece is full of umami with freshness and quality you can taste. If you’re looking for a Japanese spot that’s tasty, fresh, and full of vibes, Zutto is the place you need to check out.
reviews.author: itzelenaho

reviews.text:
Absolutely delicious! The spicy miso ramen is out of this world — rich, flavorful, and perfectly balanced. Sushi was super fresh and tasty. Great selection of Japanese snacks and sides, plus affordable and solid beer options.

Zutto hits the sweet spot between quality and price — definitely one of the best value spots around. Highly recommended for a laid-back yet authentic Japanese-American dining experience!
reviews.author: Artur St

personalization.forUser: Ichiro Sushi is a local sushi option that caters to Alex's fondness for Japanese cuisine.

places.address: 135 Bowery, New York, NY 10002, USA

reviews.text:
This AYCE bbq and sushi spot in Bowery is a great dinner or lunch spot with friends or for a date. The interior is decorated with Japanese posters and has private booths for you to enjoy your BBQ at. You order on an iPad and your food is brought out to you soon after. Price for dinner is ~$50, and on Tuesdays it's AYCD hot sake!

We ordered a variety of meats as well as appetizers and sashimi. The appetizers were pretty solid. I enjoyed their seaweed salad and seafood pancake. Although their takoyaki was good, I felt like it was a bit too oily. The meat was alright. Although they had good sauces and spices to dip it in, I felt like the quality was a bit too tough for me. The sushi/sashimi was good—better than I expected! Our favorite cut of the night actually ended up being the garlic shrimp. I ended my meal with their jelly appetizer/dessert. Wish there were more options for their AYCE package, but overall, not bad!
reviews.author: Mia Huynh

reviews.text:
We came here for a company party with around 30 people and this was accompanied in the back room, where we sat at 6 tables and different fees for Adults of $48 and $24 for kids, the options were impressive for an All you can eat sushi, sashimi and BBQ were all options that were plentiful but lack the depth of flavor.
We were impressed how helpful the staff was as it was a Saturday night and the restaurant was busy.
The meat was tender need to be cooked well and the entrees lack something that we cannot put my stamp on.
reviews.author: E. L (Ny Foodie)

reviews.text:
Came for lunch + dinner
lunch which is sorta worth it for the AYCE part, options extremely limited but for the price in the 20s isn't to bad. Service is basic just take and come with the dishes, and one perk is you get your own booth so you get privacy
Meats - 3/10
Sushi - 5/10
Others - 3/10
Dinner for 50$ (60ish after tax/tip) not worth (avoid), the only difference between lunch and dinner is the sashimi, and that's extremely limited and quality of fish is subpar at best... (a lot of better places for dinner but if no choice might as well) only reason I came was I got influenced because it said "AYCD sake tuesdays" and I guess it wasn't the case

reviews.text: Dining experience that’s as much fun as it is flavorful. The conveyor belt — or kaiten — glides past tables laden with sushi, small plates, and desserts, all under protective domes. Guests scoop up items as they pass, and special orders (like ramen) are delivered via a separate high-speed belt or by robot servers  .
reviews.author: Alek Lozan

reviews.text: I feel like the star rating for this place is not high enough! I am an avid sushi lover, and stumbled into this place for lunch one day while at the mall. Its pretty popular and always has a line out the door but the staff really are doing their best. I always have a great time here, and the revolving sushi is so much fun! And for sushi its really quite affordable and high quality fish. I reccomend the charred scallop with mayo. Its always warm and fresh. My partner takes me here for date nights beacause he knows its my favorite. Its really worth a visit!
reviews.author: Kaitlyn Henderson

reviews.text:
This is my second time at this Kura location and I found the quality decreased significantly since my last visit. The fish was very thinly sliced with 2x the rice. My favorite was the seared scallop with Japanese mayo but when requesting "light rice" it seems like they just threw the scallop on top of some rice.

Additionally, there was barely any sushi on the belt. A majority of my plates had to be ordered manually which took away from the experience.

For  $3.95 a plate, it was very disappointing.

Very cute French spot, love the decor.
Bar seats suit for low number parties, also comfortable seats for party of more.

Banana pudding taste like a very moist banana bread (I guess that’s what a pudding supposed to taste like 🤣🤣)
The profiteroles were delicious as well!
Great place for couples and friends.
reviews.author: Samantha Yuan

reviews.text: Le Crocodile was fantastic. I wasn’t sure what to expect but I pleasantly surprised with how good the food was. The menu is unique. Entree I got the bistro steak frites, it was good not great but tried the roast chicken from my friend it was delicious. My other friends got the duck breast and really liked it. The sticky banana date pudding was so good didn’t last more than 30 seconds on our table hahah. Will definitely be returning to this spot! Great place for a date or dinner with friends

There’s also a rooftop; looked nice but only saw it on the way out. Will try next time

reviews.text: Freakin' loved this place. Wife go the french dip & I got the banana french toast. Maybe a top 10 french toast I've ever had. The caramelized banana. The candied walnuts. The smoked bourbon syrup. It all worked so perfectly together. Would 100% order again.
reviews.author: Nick McCaskill

reviews.text:
This place is super cute, it is kind of like a slightly downmarket version of Majorelle on the upper east side. The decor is very similar, with plants everywhere coming from the ceiling. The temperature inside was very good. Fans inside give a breeze and not too cold.

The food was exceptional. I have the spicy lamb burger, with no English muffin and it came with really good fries and sauce for everything. The burger was perfect it was tender but firm and the goat cheese was not raw which is usually the down side of ordering a burger with goat cheese.

My boyfriend says he liked the eggs Benedict and it was “fire” and he “wants to stay here”. (Not sure what that means exactly) Unfortunately rooftop isn’t opened. Only on weekends.

The drinks are good too we had Bloody Maria with tequila, one with Mexcal and Rose.

Our waiter was Diego. He was amazing on point and very friendly. He had at least ten tables and he isn’t breaking a sweat.

Overall I definitely recommend it and also go on the weekend so you can go the rooftop.

reviews.text: The service amazing. For 2 people they offered a 2 person table, outside or inside, they sat us right away. The food was Fast and tasted fresh. However, the Sunday pancake was amazing. It’s was like a mini fluffy yellow cake with delicious buttered maple all over. not a maple taste but like a chocolaty buttery nutty flavor. “It was like a reward”. We enjoyed it the most. Overall we understand the hype and definitely recommend to try it for yourself.
reviews.author: Mar Ta

reviews.text:
I've been to Sunday in Brooklyn several times for both brunch and dinner. Brunch certainly gets busy but its a fun time - make a reservation. The food, service and drinks are always lovely - Thomas the bartender is incredible!
I recommend trying the Sage Fright brunch cocktail, the Wood Roasted Half Chicken for dinner and the S'mores soft serve for dessert. The S'mores latte is fun too for all the s'mores fans.
reviews.author: Ryan Woodcox

reviews.text:
Visited Sunday in Brooklyn for brunch and honestly, wow. We got the pistachio hummus with wood-fired flatbread — probably the richest, most flavorful meze I’ve ever had. A total must-try (and so generous we couldn’t even finish it!).

Also ordered the warm grain bowl, and it arrived in what felt like 5 minutes — unbelievably fast service. The bowl itself was pure comfort: warm, rich, and beautifully balanced. The eggs were cooked like a soufflé — soft and melting — topped with a gigantic half avocado and a generous handful of pepitas (which I love and rarely see done this well). The rice underneath was so delicious.

Finished with a cappuccino, served instantly in a lovely porcelain cup — the perfect touch to end brunch.

Our server was incredibly kind and attentive, checking in often to make sure everything was perfect. Honestly, one of the best brunch experiences we’ve had in
reviews.author: Beyza Akk

An impeccable experience from start to finish. I will definitely come back and highly recommend this place without hesitation.

Incredible food and unreliable service

The host and first server were rude to our friend who arrived before us. We had a couple other servers stop by to fill water, take orders, or ask about dessert. Service felt both rushed and inattentive

That being said, food was amazing. Highly recommend the lamb shank tagine

That said, portions were on the small side for the price (we spent around $90–$100), so just keep that in mind. When we asked if the mezze came with sourdough, the waitress said yes, but then the owner(I assume) asked us to order it separately ($5). Not a big deal, but small gestures like that could go a long way in making guests feel more welcome.
The biggest downside was the noise — it was really loud inside, which made it hard to relax or have a proper conversation. Overall, we loved the food but probably wouldn’t come back just because of the atmosphere.
reviews.author: Beyza Akk

reviews.text: We love this place!! Amazing drinks and food, but our favorite part is Emil - he has made us feel so welcome every time we come. Always remembering us and our orders. He has such incredible energy - really makes us come back time and time again. Highly recommend!!
reviews.author: Sarah Najjar

reviews.text:

I had the drink of the day, a blood orange spritz, and it was solid. The food? Also, a win. The chicken shawarma was layered with flavor, so so good. I’ll definitely be coming back for it again. The pita? Fresh, fluffy and just right.

Bonus points for accepting InKind and Blackbird. That alone sealed the deal for a return visit.

Would definitely recommend to anyone who is looking for a great brunch spot.
reviews.author: Chris C

reviews.text:
Honestly had a very underwhelming experience at this restaurant. The highlight of the meal was the appetizers- the lamb tartar was really good but it was extremely greasy and did not have enough to cut on the oil and grease.

I was not a fan of the baba ganoush and the smoked hamachi crudo. The hamachi was extremely fishy and did not taste fresh at all. The lamb could have had more flavor, and the brick chicken was dry.

the ambiance was really nice though with the dim lighting!

The apple olive oil cake was pretty dense as well. It was too dense and not light enough- what we thought an olive oil cake should taste like.

The service was great though. Overall it was decent, was not too impressed for the price. Would not come again.
reviews.author: Jessica Wong

This place is so warm and personal yet stylish and elegant, we love it. The food is imaginative and well made.
The lamb shank is out of this world- nice crust, falling off the bone, in cherry sauce - one of the best things we ate this year.
We were treated to a grilled halloumi in blueberry sauce with pistachios that was a perfect balance of sweet and tart and savory.
reviews.author: Tania StGeorge

reviews.text: The food was decent, just enough to give a 4. But overall it was extremely slow service, and they did not handle the orders well. Forgetful and very delayed courses. I waited over 45 minutes for one course to the next. That definitely ruined the experience for me but I won’t go as far as to give 3 stars being that there was no rudeness or any attitude problems with the staff. Simply just slow and forgetful service. The burger was assembled in a way where the ingredients will slip out which you can’t even enjoy the experience, but flavor wise it was good. The best thing to me surprisingly was the chicken sandwich. Great flavor,texture, and not super messy to eat. The pancakes were mid I didn’t like the overly runny yet grainy texture. Not inedible or anything, I just expected a lot better flavor and texture from it. Overall the chicken sandwich itself and the quality of food just gets them to a 4 star for me. If it was out of 10 I’d give this spot a 7 really to be fair. But yea try it out yourself and maybe your experience will be better who knows.

reviews.text: Such a great spot! The ricotta pancakes were amazingly fluffy and just sweet enough. The crispy chicken sandwich and fries totally hit the spot. Staff was nice even though it was packed, and the outdoor seating’s perfect for a sunny day.
reviews.author: Yesse Perez

reviews.text: The server/ host with long gray hair said we couldn’t sit at a table due to not having a reservation so we sat at the bar. We noticed that there were at least two open tables the entire time we were there. We waited a long time for menus and for someone to ask for our drink orders. I asked for a menu due to waiting so long time and was told by the same person as before that the bartender would handle us. The bartender didn’t show up for the first 30 mins were seated. When a different server finally took our order, she rushed us and asked if we wanted her to come back when we were ready to order but it was like a 30 second pause in ordering so not long at all. The space was very cramped and hard to feel comfortable in. People kept bumping into me while I was eating. The food was good although nothing super special and between the negative vibe from the servers and the tight space, the experience was very poor.
reviews.author: Catherine Gray

They have a tight, focused menu and the only dish that appealed to me was sold out at 7.30pm on a Sunday. Sadly. So i had biscuits and gravy. Outstanding gravy. reviews.author: Hilary P

reviews.text: I had a quick order and puck up in this sweet place and couldn’t be happier with the service provided along with the food quality. From the first seconds I entered the place I got this warm, homie, cozy dinner feeling. Girls who work here are super nice. One of them helped me with my order customization as I don’t eat all the ingredients offered initially on the menu. She was very understanding and real professional. Food was prepared clean and fast. I lived the sandwich I ordered. There were some tempting pies on display. One of the tables was a family with little kids and they all were having a blast! The rest of the guests also seemed to be very comfortable. You could tell this place is more than just a place to grab a bite. Definitely coming back. Prices are fair, flavor was amazing, people and the facility also amazing!
reviews.author: Cho

reviews.text: I absolutely loved my meal at Pies n’ Thighs! The combination of crispy chicken tenders with the incredible, buttery biscuit was heavenly comfort food. The baked beans were the perfect savory side. I finished with a slice of their pecan pie, which was rich and perfectly sweet. Highly recommend!
reviews.author: Scott Fulmer

places.address: 148 Meserole St, Brooklyn, NY 11206, USA

reviews.text: The atmosphere felt very intimate, it was dark but inviting and a great spot for a date. Service was phenomenal, they were very attentive and gave great recommendations. The cocktails were a 9/10, I had a spicy mango drink. The arepas were incredible but the number one dish was the bollitos pelones. Highly recommended. The baby shark dish was our least favorite but each dish was plated with care and very aesthetically pleasing.
reviews.author: Jonny Loero

reviews.text: Tried Venezuelan food for the first time and it didn’t disappoint. The whole spot had a warm vibe with a really inviting ambiance. Drinks were flavorful and a little strong in a good way. The food was the star though. The red snapper on tostones was fire, perfect coating and great flavor. The brisket with black beans and egg was incredibly flavorful and the meat was super tender. Overall, a really nice experience.
reviews.author: Joshua Dyer

reviews.text:
We went to Casa Ora last night to celebrate my birthday, and I’m still thinking about every single bite. The asado negro alone deserves its own love letter. If you’ve never had it, imagine a piece of beef that has been brined, marinated, and slow-cooked for hours until it becomes as tender as butter, then finished with a deep, glossy caramelization of papelón that gives you that slightly charred, smoky sweetness. It is the kind of dish that stops conversation at the table, an art piece with soul.

And everything else? Perfection with nostalgia woven in.
The plantains, the mini cachapas, the tequeños, and a pan de jamón so good it could make your abuela cry, warm, tender, slightly sweet, salty, comforting. Every plate felt like someone was inviting us into their home, letting us taste the food their family grew up on, the food that fills the kitchen on a Sunday afternoon.

Casa Ora is full of heart. You can feel the love, the purpose, the passion in every corner, not just in the dishes but in the way the team carries themselves. It is rare to find a place that feeds you and moves you at the same time.

This is the restaurant you will rave about.
The one you will bring friends to, brag about, and keep thinking about long after you leave.

An unforgettable meal, and a perfect birthday.
Thank you, Casa Ora. 💛
reviews.author: U by Dr Jones

places.address: 200 Park Ave S, New York, NY 10003, USA

reviews.text: Fantastic experience! A must if you enjoy Tacos and Mexican/Hispanic culture. The music, the food, the service - it was such an enjoyable time entering this space in NYC on my first night (2nd time visiting) - truly felt the beauty of this city. *Best Taco* - STEAK, 2nd Best - CACTUS! The guac. with nachos is out of this world - never knew you could use the word depth to describe a guacamole, believe me, you gotta try it! N.B. No seating available.

reviews.text:

reviews.text: The tortillas are made fresh to order, I always go for corn tortillas. My go to meat choice is carne asada or al pastor. Their horchata and tamarind water is good. As a Mexican I appreciate their choice of music, so many throw backs.

reviews.text:
TL;DR: Flavorful tacos and fast service in a tiny restaurant with no seating or public restroom.

Employees were friendly and good music was playing over the retro stereo system. The tacos are approx $6 with the pork taco being $1-2 less than all the others. Don’t let the lower price fool you, you’re getting a great pork taco with tons of flavor.

This location has counters but no stools, so  you’re supposed to stand, eat and drink, and leave.
reviews.author: Quentin Hodges

reviews.text: The tacos cost about $7 each. It's a great place for a quick lunch break. There is counter space all around the place to eat at, but no seating is available. It's fast, yummy, and efficient.
reviews.author: Delphine Ettinger (Ashes57)

reviews.text:
Small taqueria, but big enough. Contemporary Mexican music playlist, which was cool.
I had only the Crispy Fish Tacos (voted the best in the City by New York Magazine), and they were excellent.
Even better: by luck I visited there on a Tuesday (apparently, Taco Tuesday), and I got their 2 for 1 deal. So, two ample fish tacos cost me $4.65.
I'll be back!
reviews.author: Michael Vinson

personalization.forUser: Rosie's fits Alex's preferences because it serves Mexican food, which is listed as one of Alex's favorite cuisines.

places.address: 29 E 2nd St #5e, New York, NY 10003, USA

reviews.text:
Went here on a cold Saturday night after seeing Pozole Verde on the menu which is very difficult to find in NYC. Had reservations so was seated very quickly despite it being quite busy. We had a round of cocktails which were all very tasty and ordered a few items to share and each got our own individual green pozoles.

The Pozole Verde was good but thought there was a bit too much star anise flavoring and not enough cilantro and jalapeño/serrano peppers (I was hoping for a bit of a spicy kick). The tlayuda was the other highlight which people descrive as a Mexican pizza where a tortilla is the dough. Overall, really enjoyed the meal here and would definitely come back to try other menu items.
reviews.author: Alan C

reviews.text: I came for dinner and had an amazing time! I ordered the enchiladas suizas,not spicy at all and portion was fare, I had the guacamole with salsa and chips too,very good as well. And for drinks I had the guava paloma. It was really good too! Place is kind of big,so perfect for big parties and they have in the middle this nice tortilla maker.
reviews.author: Karen Contreras

reviews.text:
This place is always packed on Friday and Saturday evenings. We tried a several dishes here: guac and chips, quesadillas, taquitos, enchiladas, gelato, and churros. Pretty disappointed at the flavor of the dishes. The only good ones were the quesadillas and the churros.

However, the margs here were delicious. The coco loco (coconut and banana) was a great balance of sweetness and bite. Go to this restaurant for the drinks, not the food.
reviews.author: Dhruv Patel

reviews.text:
This spot really surprised me! I thought it came across a bit divey, a bit dark. I had a really great drink of their cocktail menu, switched to a margarita that I didn't like as much, and ordered tacos. The bartender explained the top three on the menu (chicken, fish, and something else) were the crowd-friendly ones and the really fun ones were at the bottom of the list.
I went safe and it was fine, but his words echoed in my mind. You only live once so I ordered the beef tongue and the beef head or whatever it's called. The tongue was good, I would eat it again, but the beef head was *incredible*, so spicy, so good! A must-eat-again taco
reviews.author: L Smith

reviews.text:
Not a dive bar as it appear, well maybe it still is but it has great AFFORDABLE apparently California style Mexican (well great for NYC). Been coming for years and have recommended to many people. Comfort food vibe, my fav is the chilaquiles. However the food isn't 100% consistent imo or maybe they got a new main line cook or something. Delicious free chips and salsa and super affordable for NYC. Great for food w friends and drinks, I like brunch the best because of the chilaquiles but do not go next door, this place has 10x better food though it looks nicer next door
Check them out!!!
reviews.author: Samantha J Lozada

reviews.text: Amazing service and amazing Tacos. I had cecina, carnitas and shrimp and it all tasted great. Another amazing thing is the price, great price for great food and service.
reviews.author: George Daniel

places.address: 43 Canal St, New York, NY 10002, USA

reviews.text:
Third time dining. Was a bit disappointed with quality of food. Tortilla was served almost cold and was more of a frittata with eggs and leeks. Shrimp head was good. Calamari also came almost in salad style in winter with cold onions. Off-season temperatures with food disappointed us. Room was also very cold to dine in, we asked if heaters could be turned on but servers just said they’ll see and never turned it on.

Burger was good.

Fish came really buttery… almost excessively. But was fine.
reviews.author: A

reviews.text: My partner and I visited Cervos for the last dinner of our trip to NYC. Overall we enjoyed dinner but it probably wouldn’t be somewhere we would recommend/return. We ordered the prawns and clams for starter but unfortunately they forgot our clams. We also ordered the sourdough but that was pretty dry and clearly had been cut hours ago. We ordered the skate and chicken for main. The skate was ok but not something we would order again. The chicken was amazing and probably one of the best chicken dishes of this type we have ever had, was really really delicious. The waiting staff were great when our dishes were forgotten (/generally)  we were offered a glass of wine on the house. Being sat on the “chef table” whilst sounded good was pretty awkward/weird when the chef asked us to move, through the waitress, as we had been sat too close to the serving spot. Overall the restaurant had a good vibe but would not recommend sitting on the counter by the chefs.
reviews.author: Andrew Russell

reviews.text: The food and service were 👌👌👌 i really wanted to try their prawn head but the menu has changed. A lot of food were sour but right level of sourness. This is a perfect date spot. Piri piri chicken and croquettes were mediocre tbh but other seafood options were amazing

Excellent cocktails and nice food presentation.  The happy hour nachos with meat was a really tasty but relatively light dinner for me.  Yum.

Was disappointed with this place. The service was EXTREMELY slow. They also didn’t bring out our chips (we ordered chips and salsa and chips and guac) until after we had our entrees? I liked the ambience of the place and the drinks were good. But the food is mid and incredibly overpriced which is unacceptable in a city with so many better food options.

reviews.text: 🌮We happened to stumble upon this restaurant by chance, and the experience was unexpectedly delightful. The drinks are exceptionally well-crafted—rich, generous, and bold—clearly reflecting the bartender’s skill and attention to detail. The tacos are equally impressive, with fresh ingredients and perfectly balanced seasoning, delivering complex layers of flavor in every bite. What truly stands out, however, is their Brutto sauce—innovative, distinctive, and incredibly creative, adding a unique twist that elevates the dishes even further. Overall, this spot impresses not only with its flavors but also with its thoughtful execution, making it well worth a casual visit—or even a deliberate detour.

reviews.text: We booked a team dinner for 10 people somewhat last minute (within 72 hours), and this could not have gone better. The food was excellent, there were no dietary worries because of the vegan menu, and the staff and service was so kind and welcoming. This is one of their smaller locations, so it probably would not have comfortably fit more than 10 for a group, but it was perfect for our needs and I would definitely go back as an individual. Thank you so much to the staff and managers for accommodating us so well!!
reviews.author: Molly

reviews.text: Didn’t think vegan food can be this good! We didn’t know that this was a 100% plant-based restaurant. But we gave it a try anyway. And it didn’t disappoint! In fact we were quite satisfied. We ordered the watermelon starter, then kale bowl, burrito bowl, and coconut dessert, all of which were really good! For the price though we expected it to be a bit more. But it’s not a dealbreaker. We enjoyed every single bite of it. The burrito bowl, goodness, they had some vegan steak in it and it was so good I couldn’t tell if it wasn’t made with meat. The texture was so real! We were sitting in the corner and it was nice as we could see the whole place. Weather was nice so some people sat outside. Give it a try. Oh, and the music was a bit loud. But we like quiet places in general. So that’s that.

reviews.text:
Had an amazing evening at Monarch Rooftop! The atmosphere here is truly something special — stylish, vibrant, and perfect for a night out in the city. The rooftop view is stunning, especially during golden hour and after sunset when the city lights come alive. It’s a great spot for both casual drinks and more dressed-up occasions.

The cocktails were excellent — well-crafted and balanced. I ordered a few signature drinks and was impressed by the presentation and flavor. They also offer a good selection of wine and spirits. The vibe was energetic without being too loud, and the music added to the overall ambiance without overpowering conversations.

The service was friendly and attentive, even though the place was busy. Staff made sure we were comfortable, and everything was brought out in a timely manner. There’s a mix of indoor and outdoor seating, but I highly recommend grabbing a spot outside if the weather’s good.

Whether you’re visiting NYC or live here and want a chic rooftop experience with great drinks and views, Monarch Rooftop is definitely worth it. I’ll be back for sure!
reviews.author: Nitiphum S.

reviews.text: Outstanding experience, my girlfriend and I went twice during our 5 day visit and both experiences were wonderful, the atmosphere is comfy and gorgeous during the day and at night it’s a great place to experience the lights of the city. The fries we ordered were okay, could use a bit more flavour but that’s the only complaint I’d have. A little pricy but it’s worth it.
reviews.author: Jane Rayment

reviews.text:
We hosted an alumni reunion happy hour at Monarch Rooftop this past June, and from start to finish, the experience was outstanding. The service was impeccable. Liz, our waitress, went above and beyond to take care of us throughout the evening. Our guests, including the dean of the school, were thoroughly impressed with how everything turned out.

There was an abundance of delicious food and drinks all night, and the atmosphere was lively yet comfortable. Everyone left feeling satisfied and already talking about returning. Monarch Rooftop truly helped make our event memorable!
reviews.author: Leighmarie Regan

personalization.forUser: With its relaxed atmosphere, 230 Fifth Rooftop Bar could be a good place for Alex to unwind, potentially offering a break from his preferred intense movie genres.

places.address: 1150 Broadway, New York, NY 10001, USA

reviews.text:
Excellent experience, stunning view & well maintained.
I visited in December 2025, right on the day of NYC snow storm, roof top was magical. Staff did good job in cleaning the snow. Igloos were well maintained & were heated. It was quite an experience to sit in a igloo & enjoy your drinks. FYI, your food & drink will be delivered in the igloo itself.
Restaurant was just one level  below to the rooftop & it was spacious, clean & decorated well.

I loved the food, specially avocado toast, fries & waffle.
reviews.author: Roam & Relish

reviews.text:
Celebrating New Year’s Eve 2026 at 230 Fifth Rooftop was nothing short of spectacular—and truly a once-in-a-lifetime experience. From the moment we arrived, it was clear that getting a table was the best decision we could have made. Having appetizers and a bottle delivered directly to our table as part of the package elevated the entire night and allowed us to relax and fully enjoy the celebration without fighting crowds. The layout was incredibly well thought out: despite being a packed NYE event, it never felt uncomfortably crowded. There were endless photo opportunities with the iconic skyline as the backdrop, making every moment feel special and memorable.

The energy throughout the night was electric. The DJs were phenomenal, keeping the vibe high and the party going nonstop. A huge shout-out to our waiter, Abu Karim, who was absolutely outstanding—attentive, professional, and on top of everything all night long. His service alone made the experience feel seamless and VIP. The open bar was fantastic, and the round rooftop igloos were such a cool touch—easy to access, warm, and perfect for enjoying drinks while taking in the views. Even better, they provided robes for guests who wanted to stay outside on the rooftop, proving that they truly thought of every detail.

Coming all the way from California, spending New Year’s Eve in New York City was a bucket-list dream—and this night at 230 Fifth was the cherry on top. From start to finish, it exceeded every expectation imaginable. Thoughtful planning, incredible atmosphere, top-tier service, and unforgettable memories made this a 10/10 experience. I would absolutely do it again without hesitation and highly recommend it to anyone looking to ring in the New Year in the most iconic way possible.
reviews.author: Richard Mena

reviews.text:
Fantastic view, very nice bar and place, very nice christmas decoration. Were 1 week in NYC, wss one of the best decorations we have seen. Film experience "kevin alone in NY" was good! Would spending time again at this beautiful place! Thanks!

reviews.text: Went to The Crown and loved it! The views are honestly some of the best in NYC (and we visit rooftop bars regularly!). The vibes were great, there’s a live DJ every week, and the drinks and bites were on point. Thanks to Elisa for organizing our visit, we’ll definitely be back soon! :)

reviews.text: Let's talk about how AMAZING the staff is at The Crown... First if all Dan, the main bartender.. he guided my wine choice and hit it out of the park.. attentive and so, so quick, to make sure no one waits.. top notch!  Deepak immediately greeted me with rhe warm and welcoming conversation, giving Dan room to move about the bar.. And Frank.. so, so funny! He gave me all of the best recommendations for nightlife after and even wrote descriptive comments about them. I loved this as a single woman traveler.. and the view... my goodness... the view is unmatched from the rooftop.. my new NY home ❤️

reviews.text: The Crown offers delicious small plates and cocktails, with great views in one of the most mellow and relaxing settings you'll ever find. They have two outdoor rooftop seating areas and an indoor seating, which are all large and spacious. The employees were very courteous and friendly, and were attentive and knowledgeable of the menu items. They offer a great happy hour deal Tuesdays to Fridays from 4 to 6, with drinks specials and half off select menu items.

reviews.text:
Amazing Night at Somewhere Nowhere!

I had such a great time at the Somewhere Nowhere comedy show — the comedians were genuinely funny, the energy was high, and the whole atmosphere felt intimate and effortless.

I also have to mention the matcha chocolate mousse and the churros with the chocolate on the side — absolutely delicious. The perfect mix of light, sweet, and comforting.

After the show I went up to the rooftop and the view took the night to another level. Beautiful skyline, great music, and such a good vibe overall.

A perfect experience from start to finish. Highly recommend!

reviews.text:
Magical rooftop!
This rooftop is an absolute gem! The service was warm and attentive from start to finish, the food was outstanding with every dish full of flavor, and the atmosphere was simply perfect—relaxed yet vibrant. Cocktails are great, yummy cosmopolitan 🍸 What truly sets it apart is the view: the Empire State Building on one side, the Hudson River sunset on the other. It’s hands down one of the best spots in the city to enjoy an unforgettable evening. Can’t wait to come back!
