reviews.text: The management at this establishment is truly incompetent. At first, they wouldn't let me in because I had a bag with me. I told them I could pay a fee and leave my bag at coat check, but they told me they didn't allow it. Then I left my bag at work and came back. When I went up to the rooftop and used the small camera I had to record the sunset, the security guard came and told me that shooting with cameras other than cell phones was prohibited. The biggest plus of this place is the view. If someone doesn't take beautiful photos of the view and share it, how will people find out and come here? The business rules are ridiculous and unreasonable. When you sit inside, you can't see clearly through the plastic mat. When you sit outside, it's difficult to see the full view from the seats and trees. Also, their food isn't very good.  I ordered the CHIMICHURRI CROQUETTES and they tasted pretty bad. The WAGYU BEEF SLIDERS were also pretty bland.

reviews.text:
Our expectation was less looking at the other reviews but to our surprise this spot was cool and had the vibe. Brunch is kids friendly which was great. During our last trip we booked another roof top & came to know not all places are allowed for kids. Staffs were nice inspite of their busyness. Heard this Magic Hour rooftop is part of Moxy hotel. Hence to skip the driving booked a room there for 2 days but didn’t realise there were different Moxy hotels in NYC. Had to drive and pay for parking separately.

Wasn’t over crowded since it was afternoon hour. My kid enjoyed & so did we!

reviews.text: I had the opportunity to visit the rooftop and I thought it was too beautiful and pleasant a place, beautiful to take pictures and spend a pleasant time with friends or as a couple, I was attended by the waitress Mariana, she was very nice, friendly and charismatic, her attention made the experience too pleasant, she explained the whole menu to me and made me several recommendations, thanks to her recommendation I tried the martini espresso and the Moira rose, thank you Mariana your attention was incredible, I loved the Moira rose! I loved the place and the attention. I want to come back for the summer!
reviews.author: Adriana Vanegas

reviews.text: I understand why this place is one of the best rooftops in NYC. I was so impressed with the decor & the atmosphere the vibes were definitely it. Loved how they had places where you could take photos. Could see this being a spot that you definitely go to for brunch with the girls to take them pics. The service was a little off, there was a period of time where our waitress had disappeared and we couldn’t get a few things that we needed. When we had booked this reservation we were excited to get a full experience cause we have stayed at the Moxy for a decade but never have been up to the rooftop for brunch . So once we sat down I knew I wanted to get the pancakes for sure . We were torn between the Crème brûlée french toast or the cotton candy pancakes. I am more of a pancake person than French toast. Once we got the pancakes , I realized that with the cotton candy alone was very very sweet. But on top of that the pancakes themselves were super dry, so I wasn’t impressed. Even after I had tried them several ways to see if one was better than the other, with just the cotton candy alone & syrup. One with the apples & syrup & one with the blueberries with syrup. No matter what I got super dry. My husband had with the the banana foster & enjoyed it. The eggs, bacon, home fries and salad was the plate I enjoyed the most! I will give that you definitely are paying for just the atmosphere. I would definitely go again and try a few other things before completely saying if I’d go back again or not. The music also was definitely created by millennials! All the songs were hitting.

Beyond making excellent drinks, you can genuinely tell he is hardworking, driven, and truly passionate about the restaurant industry.

Tsenam took the time to connect with us, made thoughtful recommendations, and elevated the entire rooftop experience. Service like his is what keeps people coming back. If you find yourself at Refinery Rooftop, do yourself a favor and sit at the bar with Tsenam. He is a standout and an asset to the team.

reviews.text: Visited Mr. Purple and really enjoyed the experience. The rooftop has amazing views of the city and a cool outdoor space that includes a swimming pool, which adds to the whole vibe. The atmosphere feels lively without being overwhelming. I was also pleasantly surprised that the drinks weren’t super expensive, and they actually tasted great. reviews.author: Manan Shah

reviews.text: Perched atop the Hotel Indigo on the Lower East Side, Mr. Purple stands as one of New York City’s most stylish rooftop bars and nightlife destinations. The design is sleek and industrial-chic, with reclaimed wood, metal finishes, and loft-inspired décor that perfectly complements its downtown edge. Guests are immediately drawn to the sweeping skyline views, which stretch from Midtown’s iconic towers to the bridges over the East River, making it a quintessential spot for sunset cocktails. The venue features both intimate terraces and a lively main space, including a poolside deck that elevates its exclusivity. reviews.text:
I recently tried the high tea at Nubeluz, and it turned out to be a memorable and beautifully executed experience. Nubeluz is known for its skyline views and modern atmosphere, and those elements definitely elevate the high tea. The moment you walk in, you’re greeted with a panoramic sweep of Manhattan that immediately sets a luxurious tone. The space feels contemporary and stylish, very different from the traditional settings you find in classic afternoon teas.

The food was excellent — thoughtful, refined, and visually impressive. The savory bites had clean flavors, and the pastries were delicate without being overly sweet. Everything tasted fresh, and the presentation added to the experience. The tea selection was also quite good, and the staff were helpful in guiding us through the choices. Service was attentive but relaxed, giving the experience a more modern lounge feel.

Compared to The Ritz in London, the difference is clear but enjoyable in its own way. The Ritz is all about tradition, ceremony, and formality — the classic tiered trays, the live music, and the unmistakable old-world charm. Nubeluz, on the other hand, feels contemporary, sleek, and more playful. Instead of ornate décor and formal tea service, you get dramatic city views and a stylish, cosmopolitan vibe.

The Ritz London focuses on preserving an elegant ritual, while Nubeluz offers a reinterpretation of afternoon tea that fits New York’s energy. Both are excellent experiences, but they appeal to different moods: the Ritz when you want classic refinement, and Nubeluz when you’re in the mood for something modern with a bit of sparkle.

Overall, high tea at Nubeluz is a beautiful, delicious, and uniquely New York experience, and it stands strong even when compared with iconic high teas abroad.

reviews.text:
Sterling Lake, named for the silvery barked beach trees in this area, is located off Sterling Mine  Road on Old Forge Rd. I must admit, it's somewhat confusing the way the nearby lakes are named. We are referring to Sterling Lake. There are also Little Sterling Lake and Sterling Forest Lake(also called Blue Lake on the IBM Corporate Office Park. IBM's nickname is "Big Blue"). Mining for iron in this area was taking place before the Revolutionary War. The links of chain across the Hudson River to prevent British warships from sailing past West Point were made in the original foundry at Sterling Mine. It was intended to halt progress of warships. Cannon placements in West Point and strategic hill tops would lob cannon shot  down onto the stranded vessels. This was a physically impractical engineering design the chain failing under its own weight. And British naval strategists knew how risky a notion it would be to travel up the Hudson River while the Continental Army held such a strategic and formidable fortress. It was a stalemate. But the mines held an important place for it made the weapons needed to win the war.
Mine shafts travel under thIs lake. It is a watershed. It's clean water is part of the Hudson Highlands Watershed and provides water for reservoirs below it. Hiking, mountain biking and cross country skiing trails are available for use in this 20,000 acre park. The Frank Lautenburg Visitors Center and parking area sits on a prominence on the south side of the lake. You could hike the lake and many connected trails from here or take a short walk to see the restored  original blast furnace or crumbling remains of later iron works operations.  But now to the present.  Last year, two climate related events devastated Sterling Forest and its trails are closed indefinitely. There is no time line for remediating damage here. A May, 2024 violent change of season storm brought the jet stream tumbling to earth, which destroyed the forest as though it was a clear cutting operation. We spoke to  a sawyer by the visitors center. Brian was his name and he told us to look at his YouTube videos of what he does. Just Google Brian NV to see his videos. He hikes miles into the woods to open trails with  a chain saw. Then, on November 9, 2024, after a long drought, the Jenkins fire scorched the area. It was a quick moving forest fire that may actually be beneficial to old growth trees by removing underbrush that can choke and rob these trees of nutrients. But it's a nice ride to get here and see the big blow down and mine operations and visitor center displays of dioramas, mine artifacts and wildlife.
